Her daily walks are part of her development before she can be safely released back into the wild.

Keepers at the zoo have also built the joey a home where she can dig burrows and forage for her own food.

‘She’s really learning how to be a wombat. Her paws are already toughening up and she’s quite happy digging about on her own,’ said Evelyn.

When the time comes for Chloe to be released back into the wild she will first be transferred to a wombat ‘halfway house’.

But Evelyn admitted she’ll be a little sad to lose her. ‘I’ve been doing this job for a long time, but it’s always hard to say goodbye. I like to think I’ve toughened up, but sometimes I’m still a wuss,’ she said.

